    "post_id": "2862745324884948500",
    "filename": "2022-06-17_2862745324884948513.jpg",
    "description": "getting back to normal life has been hard for me. i hear every one around me and all their plans, summer festivals and holidays and life in general, all the people i know seem to be pregnant, starting businesses, writing books. and here i am, getting back to normal life means getting back to being incurably ill. for about 10 days i had myself convinced i could live a ‚Äúnormal‚Äù life, granted one with extra naps and antibiotics and pills that are keeping me alive, but still a life without hospital and doctors, where no one knew i had cancer. i went to visit ancient sites and walked around in my swimming suit all day, hair wet with pool water or sea salt, watching sun sets on cliffs, going on all kinds of adventures. and then i came back and the day after that i went to the hospital to get an infusion and got into a traumatic situation and i was very much here again. in a life that feels like a stalemate, seeing everyone growing and living and planning while i‚Äôm wondering if that was the last holiday i‚Äôm ever able to go on\n\ni‚Äôm not ready to be back here, im grieving all the versions of me that could have been. i‚Äôm tired of being sick, being in treatment, being reduced to this and still there is no other way. for now i‚Äôm allowing myself to feel it all, to grieve and reel. to feel so alone in all this. for now i‚Äôm getting used to being here again. being here still. \n_\n#thisiswhatcancerlookslike #chronicillness #stage4needsmore #coloncancer #braf #treatmentfatigue #medicaltrauma #incurablyill #becoming #livingwithcancer #grief",
    "likes": 132,
