    "post_id": "3011849596716385300",
    "filename": "2023-01-09_3011849596716385206.jpg",
    "description": "ìäì a story i want to tell that gives me hope living in the void ìäì\n\ntwo years ago i was in kind of the same situation as i‚Äôm in right now. to sketch the scene: i had gotten diagnose with bowel cancer and mets to both ovaries in oktober 2020, was in immense pain and could barely keep food down and they scheduled an emergency situation (a hipec, which i later learned is one of the hardest ops you can go through). back then we were still very much working on curing me and i was put on a maintenance chemo (folfox) in the middle of december. fast forward to the beginning of february, 3 rounds in, and i was in immense pain, having all the side effects, overal miserable and having a very bad feeling about the chemo. an er visit led to a scan which led to the words ‚Äúwe can see something off at your bowel but we can‚Äôt tell if it‚Äôs just an infection or recurrence we will need an mri‚Äù. (if any of this sounds familiar it‚Äôs because it is familiar). a week later we learned that my cancer had returned and the chemo wasn‚Äôt working and we had to pivot and that‚Äôs how i got put on the immuno therapy(encorafenib + cetuximab) that i have been stable on for two years now.\n\ni was terrified, there were no guarantees, this might be the tipping point. the only saving grace was that immuno therapy would normally mean a lot less side effects. i would have never hoped for one med to stop working, i would have never hoped for a recurrence, i would have never hoped for the ‚Äúwe don‚Äôt know but we can try‚Äù. i didn‚Äôt know it back then because it felt like everything was swept from under me but it was a true blessing. the immunotherapy worked, first it shrunk my tumor and then everything stayed stable. also, the side effects were much more manegeable. i had been surviving under my chemo regime but immuno gave me the possibility to start living again. i got to do so many things because of this therapy, i got two years of life. \n\nit was a true tower moment where something was falling away for something better but i would never have let the security of what i knew, go on my own so i needed some help. \n\ncontinued in pictures\n\n#thisiswhatcancerlookslike #incurableillness #livinginthevoid #bowelcancer",
    "likes": 366,
    "comments": 22,
    "views": 0
